  "prompt": "What are the signs of a poorly-written scientific paper?",
  "response": "Here are some signs of a poorly-written scientific paper:\n\n1. Methodological Issues\n- Weak or unclear research design\n- Insufficient sample size\n- Poor experimental controls\n- Lack of statistical rigor\n- Methodological steps not adequately described\n\n2. Writing and Structure Problems\n- Unclear or poorly organized writing\n- Excessive jargon\n- Grammatical and spelling errors\n- Inconsistent formatting\n- Lack of clear narrative flow\n\n3. Data and Analysis Concerns\n- Inappropriate statistical analysis\n- Overstated or unsupported conclusions\n- Selective reporting of results\n- Cherry-picking data\n- Lack of acknowledgment of study limitations\n\n4. Referencing and Citation Shortcomings\n- Outdated or irrelevant references\n- Insufficient citation of relevant prior work\n- Self-citation without justification\n- Misrepresentation of previous research\n\n5. Ethical Red Flags\n- Potential conflicts of interest not disclosed\n- Plagiarism\n- Data manipulation\n- Fabrication or falsification of results\n\n6. Presentation Issues\n- Poor quality figures/tables\n- Graphs or charts that mislead\n- Lack of clarity in data presentation\n- Inadequate legends or captions\n\nThese indicators can help critically evaluate the quality and credibility of scientific publications.",
